") (link ((href . "https://blog.avas.space/is-blogging-romantic/") (rel . "alternate"))) (published nil "2025-06-10T19:53:00+00:00")) (entry nil (id nil "https://notesfromnick.bearblog.dev/the-version-of-trans-that-no-one-talks-about-anymore/") (title nil "The Version of Trans That No One Talks About Anymore") (updated nil "2025-06-10T13:10:00+00:00") (author nil (name nil "notesfromnick") (email nil "hidden")) (content ((type . "html")) "<p><em>—by a man who’s lived it</em></p>
<p>I’m trans. I’ve changed my body, my voice, my entire freaking life because not doing so would’ve eventually killed me. I didn’t choose this path to make a statement or escape misogyny. I chose it because I needed to survive. Because this is the only way I can exist and still be able to breathe.</p>
<p>But the version of “trans” I see celebrated online doesn’t look anything like the life I’ve built. What I see now is a word that’s been stretched beyond all recognition; used as an aesthetic, a non conforming political gesture. And the people who use it that way? They’ve never stared down the barrel of this identity the way I have.</p>
<p>Being trans, for me, is a risk. I have an invisible target tattoed on my back. It’s being clocked in public. It’s walking into a bathroom or changing room and preparing for confrontation. It’s feeling my heart rate spike every time a stranger’s eyes linger just a little <em>too</em> long. It’s the fear of losing my job, my home, my family, and any safety net I might have. If someone ever decides “you look wrong” it wouldn’t just mean a bad day, <strong>it could cost me my life.</strong></p>
<p>People who call themselves trans but <em>choose</em> to <em>never</em> transition socially, emotionally, physically or medically don’t carry that same weight. And I’m tired of pretending that’s not a huge difference in experience and meaning.</p>
<p>If you haven’t faced dysphoria…<br />
If you haven’t fought to change your body, your voice, your documents and your name, or how the world physically sees you…<br />
If you haven’t risked safety, comfort, or stability just to live a day as yourself…<br />
Then you’re not walking the same road I am.</p>
<p><em>And that’s not hate. That’s just fucking reality.</em></p>
<p>I don’t have anything against people who are questioning, exploring, or playing with gender. That’s their business. They’re free to do as they like, who am I to say they can’t or shouldn’t? But I refuse to let that version of “trans” erase mine. Because I’m not some aesthetic variation. I’m a binary man who has bled, cried, screamed, fought, and rebuilt himself. And when people like me try to speak? We’re silenced. Called transphobic or anti-woke. Told we’re gatekeeping and to be quiet while those who’ve never paid the price get to define the entire experience and speak for us. Speak over us.</p>
<p>There should be a word for what I am.<br />
And maybe it used to be “trans.”<br />
But I’m not sure anymore.</p>
<p>All I know is I didn’t get here by swapping out pronoun pins.</p>
<p>I got here by fighting tooth and nail, with a syringe and a vial.</p>
