<h4>Frequency Illusion</h4>
<p>I'm sure you have!</p>
<p>It's been happening to me a lot lately; I don't try to find any meaning or pay too much attention to it, but I find it very amusing! It's like a fun little game.<br />
But I have to confess, sometimes a part of me tries to come up with meanings, or I act like I'm in the Matrix or something! Though I usually end up moving on very quickly after having fun for a bit.</p>
<p>My latest example of <em>Frequency Illusion</em>, aka the Baader–Meinhof phenomenon, was just a couple of days ago, when I decided to finally look up a manual for an old watch I have, which had been going off every night at around 12 am. The watch was in a box, in a room where it didn't bother anyone, but whenever I stayed up late to do things in said room, I could hear the alarm go off, three times, every five minutes, and then stop.</p>
<p><img src=\"https://bear-images.sfo2.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/skeleton/w-753-front.webp\" alt=\"W-753 - Front\" /></p>
<p>This went on for some months, and a week ago I decided it was time to do something, as I'm packing up my things for Japan, and having a watch with me could be useful, especially since I'm planning on replacing my current phone with a Japanese flip phone. I'm tired of smartphones. That reminds me, in the last couple of months I ended up &quot;acquiring&quot; 3 watches, despite never being a watch person, but that's a story for another post.</p>
<p>Where was I? Right, I had to look up the manual for my old watch; I had to know how to turn off the alarm and fix all the other settings.<br />
When I checked the model on the back, there I saw it:</p>
<p><img src=\"https://bear-images.sfo2.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/skeleton/w-753-back.webp\" alt=\"W-753 - Back\" /></p>
<p>For a little context, this watch was a gift from one of my grandparents, when I was a very young kid, just starting school, I believe? I probably wore it for two weeks before forgetting about it, and my mom ended up putting it away. Now, around 15 years later, I found it again, and the story I told you about happened.</p>
<p>So, where's the <em>Frequency Illusion</em>? Well, some years ago, like most guys in the world, I became a huge fan of Rome, everything Rome, and I still love Rome; I think about it every day, all the time! I hate how real the meme is...<br />
And one of the things I never forget about Rome is how it was founded on the 21st of April... <strong>753</strong> BC.<br />
One of my favorite dates, that I never forget and always think of, suddenly has a connection with my first watch, that I received as a gift over a decade and a half ago?<br />
Not only that, the watch is pretty good! Not very fashionable, or at least not my style, but it has a bunch of fun and useful features and modes.<br />
Feels like the kind of watch that you would wear during &quot;rough outdoor activities&quot;, like hiking, climbing a mountain, beach stuff... which... I'm gonna be doing in Japan?!</p>
<h4>What is going on?!</h4>
<p>Okay, see where I'm coming from?</p>
<p>I &quot;find&quot; an old watch, a gift from a grandparent that I love. I decide to tweak its settings after months of not paying attention to it, years if you're counting that. It is connected to one of the things I obsess over, because of the model number, and it's also gonna be super useful during this new chapter of my life in the Land of the Rising Sun?</p>
<h4>Isn't this fun?</h4>
<p>\\</p>
<h4>That's all! I hope to see you again soon! ★</h4>
